Note: ===================================================================
Note: DOCKERFILE SEMANTIC ANALYZER
Note: ===================================================================
Note: Semantic analysis for Dockerfile container definitions. Handles Docker
Note: instruction validation, multi-stage build analysis, layer optimization
Note: recommendations, and container security best practices.

Note: Part of the Translation System
Note: Location: compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/dockerfile/dockerfile_semantic.runa
Note: ===================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/dockerfile/dockerfile_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrim
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List

Note: ===================================================================
Note: AST NODE TYPE TAGS (mirror of dockerfile_parser.runa node constants)
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
The analyzer reads the integer node_type tag stored at offset 0 of every
instruction node produced by the parser. The bootstrap compiler resolves
Constants per-module, so the analyzer keeps a byte-for-byte copy of the
parser's NODE_* tag values rather than importing them. These map directly
to the instruction keyword each tag represents.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
One Constant per Dockerfile instruction kind, matching the values declared
in dockerfile_parser.runa (NODE_DOCKERFILE = 1000 root, FROM = 1001, ...).
@End Implementation

Constant NODE_DOCKERFILE as Integer is 1000
Constant NODE_FROM as Integer is 1001
Constant NODE_RUN as Integer is 1002
Constant NODE_CMD as Integer is 1003
Constant NODE_LABEL as Integer is 1004
Constant NODE_EXPOSE as Integer is 1005
Constant NODE_ENV as Integer is 1006
Constant NODE_ADD as Integer is 1007
Constant NODE_COPY as Integer is 1008
Constant NODE_ENTRYPOINT as Integer is 1009
Constant NODE_VOLUME as Integer is 1010
Constant NODE_USER as Integer is 1011
Constant NODE_WORKDIR as Integer is 1012
Constant NODE_ARG as Integer is 1013
Constant NODE_ONBUILD as Integer is 1014
Constant NODE_STOPSIGNAL as Integer is 1015
Constant NODE_HEALTHCHECK as Integer is 1016
Constant NODE_SHELL as Integer is 1017
Constant NODE_MAINTAINER as Integer is 1018

Note: ===================================================================
Note: SEMANTIC ANALYZER STRUCTURE
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Dockerfile semantic analysis tracks per-instruction state that matters
across the build: base images (FROM directives, possibly multi-stage),
named stages, exposed ports (EXPOSE), runtime ENV vars, declared VOLUMEs,
WORKDIRs, USERs, LABELs, build ARGs, the current stage cursor, and a layer
count for image-size warnings. Three parallel diagnostic streams keep
security issues, optimization advice, and hard validation errors apart so
the reporter can apply distinct severity rules.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
17 x i64 record (136 bytes, offsets 0..128): each registry slot is a List
(ordered streams like exposed_ports/security_issues; the metadata slots
environment_vars/labels/args store "key=value" strings). current_stage
points to the active stage index during a walk; layer_count is bumped on
every RUN/COPY/etc. The error_message + has_error pair behaves identically
to the cmake/cpp analyzers (sticky first-error).
@End Implementation

Type called "DockerfileSemanticAnalyzer":
    base_images as Integer
    stages as Integer
    exposed_ports as Integer
    environment_vars as Integer
    volumes as Integer
    workdirs as Integer
    users as Integer
    labels as Integer
    args as Integer
    current_stage as Integer
    layer_count as Integer
    security_issues as Integer
    optimization_warnings as Integer
    validation_errors as Integer
    validation_warnings as Integer
    error_message as Integer
    has_error as Integer
End Type

Note: ===================================================================
Note: ANALYZER CREATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
The Dockerfile analyzer is a 136-byte (17-slot) record holding 13 collection
registries plus state counters: base_images, stages, exposed_ports,
environment_vars, volumes, workdirs, users, labels, args, security_issues,
optimization_warnings, validation_errors, validation_warnings, plus
current_stage/layer_count counters and the error_message/has_error pair.
We split errors from warnings (and errors from optimization-warnings)
because Docker validation produces three severity tiers: hard syntax
errors that block builds, security issues that compromise the container,
and optimization hints that don't break anything but waste resources.
Downstream tooling treats each tier differently.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 136-byte record via Layout.allocate; returns 0 if it fails.
Creates 13 Lists wired into the analyzer at fixed offsets 0..64 and 88..112.
Initialises counter slots: offset 72 (current_stage) = 0, offset 80
(layer_count) = 0, offset 120 (error_message) = 0, offset 128 (has_error)
= 0. Returns the analyzer handle as an opaque Integer.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_dockerfile_semantic_analyzer" returns Integer:
    Note: Create Dockerfile semantic analyzer for container validation

    Let analyzer_size be 136
    Let analyzer be proc allocate from Layout with analyzer_size

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let base_images be proc list_create from List
    Let stages be proc list_create from List
    Let exposed_ports be proc list_create from List
    Let environment_vars be proc list_create from List
    Let volumes be proc list_create from List
    Let workdirs be proc list_create from List
    Let users be proc list_create from List
    Let labels be proc list_create from List
    Let args be proc list_create from List
    Let security_issues be proc list_create from List
    Let optimization_warnings be proc list_create from List
    Let validation_errors be proc list_create from List
    Let validation_warnings be proc list_create from List

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0, base_images
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8, stages
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16, exposed_ports
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24, environment_vars
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32, volumes
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40, workdirs
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48, users
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56, labels
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 64, args
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72, 0  Note: current_stage
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80, 0  Note: layer_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88, security_issues
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96, optimization_warnings
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 104, validation_errors
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 112, validation_warnings
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 120, 0  Note: error_message
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 128, 0  Note: has_error

    Return analyzer
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: AST ACCESSORS
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
The analyzer walks the parser's DockerfileAST root, whose instruction list
lives at offset 8 (a list_create list of instruction-node pointers). This
accessor isolates that single field read so the rest of the analyzer never
touches the AST layout directly - if the parser node layout changes, only
this proc updates.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for a null AST. Otherwise reads the instructions list pointer at
DockerfileAST offset 8 and returns it. The returned list is owned by the
AST; the analyzer only reads it.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_dockerfile_instructions" takes dockerfile_ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Return the ordered instruction list from a parsed Dockerfile AST

    If dockerfile_ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dockerfile_ast, 8
End Process

@Reasoning:
Every analysis pass dispatches on the instruction keyword (FROM/RUN/COPY/...)
but the parser stores the kind as an integer node_type tag at offset 0, not
a string. This accessor maps the tag to its canonical keyword string so the
Match/string_equals based dispatch elsewhere works against human-readable
keywords. Unknown tags return "UNKNOWN" so the unknown-instruction warning
path can fire.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads node_type at instruction offset 0, then returns the matching keyword
for each NODE_* constant. Null node yields "UNKNOWN".
@End Implementation

Process called "get_instruction_type" takes instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Map an instruction node's integer tag to its Dockerfile keyword

    If instruction is equal to 0:
        Return "UNKNOWN"
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 0

    If node_type is equal to NODE_FROM:
        Return "FROM"
    End If
    If node_type is equal to NODE_RUN:
        Return "RUN"
    End If
    If node_type is equal to NODE_CMD:
        Return "CMD"
    End If
    If node_type is equal to NODE_LABEL:
        Return "LABEL"
    End If
    If node_type is equal to NODE_EXPOSE:
        Return "EXPOSE"
    End If
    If node_type is equal to NODE_ENV:
        Return "ENV"
    End If
    If node_type is equal to NODE_ADD:
        Return "ADD"
    End If
    If node_type is equal to NODE_COPY:
        Return "COPY"
    End If
    If node_type is equal to NODE_ENTRYPOINT:
        Return "ENTRYPOINT"
    End If
    If node_type is equal to NODE_VOLUME:
        Return "VOLUME"
    End If
    If node_type is equal to NODE_USER:
        Return "USER"
    End If
    If node_type is equal to NODE_WORKDIR:
        Return "WORKDIR"
    End If
    If node_type is equal to NODE_ARG:
        Return "ARG"
    End If
    If node_type is equal to NODE_ONBUILD:
        Return "ONBUILD"
    End If
    If node_type is equal to NODE_STOPSIGNAL:
        Return "STOPSIGNAL"
    End If
    If node_type is equal to NODE_HEALTHCHECK:
        Return "HEALTHCHECK"
    End If
    If node_type is equal to NODE_SHELL:
        Return "SHELL"
    End If
    If node_type is equal to NODE_MAINTAINER:
        Return "MAINTAINER"
    End If

    Return "UNKNOWN"
End Process

@Reasoning:
The validators consume each instruction's arguments as a uniform ordered
List of strings regardless of how the parser stored them per node type.
FROM exposes [image, "AS", stage_name] (so arg_count>2 signals a named
stage); COPY/ADD expose [source..., destination]; RUN/CMD/ENTRYPOINT
expose [command]; EXPOSE/VOLUME expose their stored child list directly;
USER exposes [user, group?]; WORKDIR/ARG/STOPSIGNAL/MAINTAINER expose
their single string. This normalisation lets every downstream validator
read args[i] without knowing the node's internal field layout.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads node_type at offset 0 and builds a fresh List per kind from the
parser's node fields (image at FROM offset 8, stage_name at 32; command
at RUN/CMD/ENTRYPOINT offset 16; sources list at COPY offset 8 + dest at
16; ports list at EXPOSE offset 8; user at USER offset 8 + group at 16;
path at WORKDIR offset 8; name+default at ARG offsets 8/16; signal at
STOPSIGNAL offset 8; name at MAINTAINER offset 8). EXPOSE/VOLUME forward
their stored list. Empty strings are not appended so arg_count reflects
present arguments only.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_instruction_arguments" takes instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Build a uniform argument list for any instruction node

    Let result be proc list_create from List
    If instruction is equal to 0:
        Return result
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 0

    If node_type is equal to NODE_FROM:
        Let image be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 8
        Let image_present be string_is_nonempty with image
        If image_present is equal to 1:
            proc list_append from List with result, image
        End If
        Let stage_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 32
        Let stage_present be string_is_nonempty with stage_name
        If stage_present is equal to 1:
            proc list_append from List with result, "AS"
            proc list_append from List with result, stage_name
        End If
        Return result
    End If

    If node_type is equal to NODE_RUN:
        Let run_cmd be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 16
        Let run_present be string_is_nonempty with run_cmd
        If run_present is equal to 1:
            proc list_append from List with result, run_cmd
        End If
        Return result
    End If

    If node_type is equal to NODE_CMD:
        Let cmd_cmd be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 16
        Let cmd_present be string_is_nonempty with cmd_cmd
        If cmd_present is equal to 1:
            proc list_append from List with result, cmd_cmd
        End If
        Return result
    End If

    If node_type is equal to NODE_ENTRYPOINT:
        Let ep_cmd be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 16
        Let ep_present be string_is_nonempty with ep_cmd
        If ep_present is equal to 1:
            proc list_append from List with result, ep_cmd
        End If
        Return result
    End If

    If node_type is equal to NODE_COPY:
        Let copy_sources be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 8
        If copy_sources is not equal to 0:
            Let src_count be proc list_length from List with copy_sources
            Let s be 0
            While s is less than src_count:
                Let src be proc list_get from List with copy_sources, s
                proc list_append from List with result, src
                Set s to s plus 1
            End While
        End If
        Let copy_dest be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 16
        Let dest_present be string_is_nonempty with copy_dest
        If dest_present is equal to 1:
            proc list_append from List with result, copy_dest
        End If
        Return result
    End If

    If node_type is equal to NODE_ADD:
        Let add_sources be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 8
        If add_sources is not equal to 0:
            Let asrc_count be proc list_length from List with add_sources
            Let a be 0
            While a is less than asrc_count:
                Let asrc be proc list_get from List with add_sources, a
                proc list_append from List with result, asrc
                Set a to a plus 1
            End While
        End If
        Let add_dest be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 16
        Let add_dest_present be string_is_nonempty with add_dest
        If add_dest_present is equal to 1:
            proc list_append from List with result, add_dest
        End If
        Return result
    End If

    If node_type is equal to NODE_EXPOSE:
        Let ports be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 8
        If ports is equal to 0:
            Return result
        End If
        Return ports
    End If

    If node_type is equal to NODE_VOLUME:
        Let paths be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 8
        If paths is equal to 0:
            Return result
        End If
        Return paths
    End If

    If node_type is equal to NODE_USER:
        Let user be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 8
        Let user_present be string_is_nonempty with user
        If user_present is equal to 1:
            proc list_append from List with result, user
        End If
        Let group be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 16
        Let group_present be string_is_nonempty with group
        If group_present is equal to 1:
            proc list_append from List with result, group
        End If
        Return result
    End If

    If node_type is equal to NODE_WORKDIR:
        Let path be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 8
        Let path_present be string_is_nonempty with path
        If path_present is equal to 1:
            proc list_append from List with result, path
        End If
        Return result
    End If

    If node_type is equal to NODE_ARG:
        Let arg_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 8
        Let name_present be string_is_nonempty with arg_name
        If name_present is equal to 1:
            proc list_append from List with result, arg_name
        End If
        Let arg_default be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 16
        Let default_present be string_is_nonempty with arg_default
        If default_present is equal to 1:
            proc list_append from List with result, arg_default
        End If
        Return result
    End If

    If node_type is equal to NODE_STOPSIGNAL:
        Let signal be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 8
        Let signal_present be string_is_nonempty with signal
        If signal_present is equal to 1:
            proc list_append from List with result, signal
        End If
        Return result
    End If

    If node_type is equal to NODE_MAINTAINER:
        Let maint be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 8
        Let maint_present be string_is_nonempty with maint
        If maint_present is equal to 1:
            proc list_append from List with result, maint
        End If
        Return result
    End If

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
A string-presence predicate is needed across the argument builder: a parser
field is "present" when it is a non-null pointer to a non-empty string.
Centralising the test keeps the argument-list logic uniform and avoids
treating the empty-string sentinel as a real argument.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 if the handle is 0. Otherwise reads its length via StringCore and
returns 1 when length > 0, else 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "string_is_nonempty" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: True when value is a non-null handle to a non-empty string

    If value is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with value
    If length is greater than 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: MAIN ANALYSIS ENTRY POINT
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Sequences a six-phase analysis with strict ordering: structure validation
must run first to populate the instruction-derived registries (base_images,
exposed_ports, etc.); stage analysis follows because it depends on the
already-collected FROM list; image validation needs the populated base_images
list; security analysis must see the full instruction stream including
USER/RUN context; layer optimization comes next because it needs the
layer_count populated by structure validation; best-practices is last
because it consults every registry built by the prior phases. Each phase
runs even if earlier phases reported errors - the user wants a complete
diagnostics dump, not a fail-fast.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 immediately if analyzer is null. If dockerfile_ast is null,
calls set_dockerfile_semantic_error and returns 0. Calls in order:
validate_dockerfile_structure, analyze_build_stages, validate_base_images,
analyze_dockerfile_security, analyze_layer_optimization,
validate_docker_best_practices. After all six complete, reads has_error
(offset 128); returns 0 if any phase set it, else 1. Return value is
analysis-level success/failure; individual error and warning lists carry
the full diagnostic detail.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Dockerfile AST originates from untrusted source files. All instruction
arguments are validated before being added to the registries, and
security_issues is populated independently from validation_errors so
downstream tooling can apply security policy distinct from syntactic
correctness.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "analyze_dockerfile" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Perform complete semantic analysis on Dockerfile

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If dockerfile_ast is equal to 0:
        proc set_dockerfile_semantic_error with analyzer, "Null Dockerfile AST"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Phase 1: Validate instruction sequence and structure
    proc validate_dockerfile_structure with analyzer, dockerfile_ast

    Note: Phase 2: Analyze build stages and multi-stage builds
    proc analyze_build_stages with analyzer, dockerfile_ast

    Note: Phase 3: Validate base images and dependencies
    proc validate_base_images with analyzer

    Note: Phase 4: Perform security analysis
    proc analyze_dockerfile_security with analyzer, dockerfile_ast

    Note: Phase 5: Analyze layer optimization opportunities
    proc analyze_layer_optimization with analyzer, dockerfile_ast

    Note: Phase 6: Validate Docker best practices
    proc validate_docker_best_practices with analyzer, dockerfile_ast

    Let has_error be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 128
    If has_error is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: DOCKERFILE STRUCTURE VALIDATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Phase 1 validates two orthogonal properties: macro structure (FROM
placement, instruction ordering, required instructions) and micro
structure (per-instruction syntax). An empty instruction list is treated
as a hard error rather than being silently accepted, because an empty
Dockerfile produces an empty image and is almost certainly a mistake.
Order matters: FROM-placement validation runs before the per-instruction
loop so that the "FROM must come first" rule is reported before any
downstream errors that would result from a missing FROM.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads instructions list and its count via List.list_length. If count == 0,
adds "Empty Dockerfile" validation error and returns. Calls
validate_from_instruction_placement to enforce FROM-first / ARG-before-
FROM ordering. Then loops i in 0..count-1: pulls instruction at index,
calls validate_instruction_syntax(analyzer, instruction, i) (i used as
the 0-based line number for error reporting), and collect_instruction_info
to populate the per-instruction registries. Finally calls
validate_required_instructions for whole-file checks.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_dockerfile_structure" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Validate Dockerfile instruction sequence and structure

    Let instructions be proc get_dockerfile_instructions with dockerfile_ast
    If instructions is equal to 0:
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, "Empty Dockerfile"
        Return
    End If

    Let instruction_count be proc list_length from List with instructions

    If instruction_count is equal to 0:
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, "Empty Dockerfile"
        Return
    End If

    Note: Validate FROM instruction is first (or after ARG for build args)
    proc validate_from_instruction_placement with analyzer, instructions

    Note: Validate instruction sequence
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than instruction_count:
        Let instruction be proc list_get from List with instructions, i
        proc validate_instruction_syntax with analyzer, instruction, i
        proc collect_instruction_info with analyzer, instruction
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Validate required instructions
    proc validate_required_instructions with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
End Process

@Reasoning:
The Dockerfile spec mandates FROM as the first non-comment instruction
EXCEPT that ARG declarations that supply variables for the FROM line
(e.g., `ARG BASE_TAG` followed by `FROM alpine:${BASE_TAG}`) are
permitted before it. No other instruction may precede FROM because
without a base layer there's nothing for them to act on. We track this
with a single found_from flag rather than an enum because the only
states that matter are "haven't seen FROM yet" and "have seen FROM";
once found, the placement check is satisfied for the rest of the file.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads instruction_count via List.list_length. Initialises found_from=0,
i=0. Loops while i < count AND found_from == 0: pulls instruction, reads
instruction_type. If type equals "FROM", sets found_from=1 and writes 0
to analyzer offset 72 (current_stage = first stage). Otherwise, tests
for ARG; if NOT ARG, builds an error and returns. After the loop, if
found_from is still 0, adds "Missing required FROM instruction".
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_from_instruction_placement" takes analyzer as Integer, instructions as Integer:
    Note: Validate FROM instruction placement and syntax

    Let instruction_count be proc list_length from List with instructions
    Let found_from be 0
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than instruction_count and found_from is equal to 0:
        Let instruction be proc list_get from List with instructions, i
        Let instruction_type be proc get_instruction_type with instruction

        Let is_from be proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction_type, "FROM"
        If is_from is equal to 1:
            Set found_from to 1
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72, 0  Note: Set current_stage to 0
        Otherwise:
            Let is_arg be proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction_type, "ARG"
            If is_arg is equal to 0:
                Note: Non-ARG instruction before FROM
                Let error be "FROM instruction must be first (found "
                Set error to proc string_concat from StringPrim with error, instruction_type
                Set error to proc string_concat from StringPrim with error, " at line "
                Let line_label be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with i plus 1
                Set error to proc string_concat from StringPrim with error, line_label
                Set error to proc string_concat from StringPrim with error, ")"
                proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, error
                Return
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    If found_from is equal to 0:
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, "Missing required FROM instruction"
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Per-instruction syntax dispatcher. Each Docker instruction kind (FROM,
RUN, COPY, ADD, EXPOSE, ENV, WORKDIR, USER, VOLUME, LABEL, ARG, CMD,
ENTRYPOINT) has its own validator because the argument grammar and
semantic constraints differ. Unknown instructions emit a warning rather
than an error because Docker BuildKit supports extension instructions
via `# syntax=` directives - a hard error would reject valid Dockerfiles
that use newer or third-party frontends.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads instruction_type and args (Lists) from the instruction node. A
Match expression dispatches on the type string to the corresponding
per-instruction validator (validate_from_instruction,
validate_run_instruction, etc.), passing analyzer, args, line_number.
Otherwise branch builds "Unknown instruction: <type> at line <n+1>"
warning and adds it to validation_warnings.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_instruction_syntax" takes analyzer as Integer, instruction as Integer, line_number as Integer:
    Note: Validate individual instruction syntax

    Let instruction_type be proc get_instruction_type with instruction
    Let args be proc get_instruction_arguments with instruction

    Match instruction_type:
        When "FROM":
            proc validate_from_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        When "RUN":
            proc validate_run_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        When "COPY":
            proc validate_copy_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        When "ADD":
            proc validate_add_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        When "EXPOSE":
            proc validate_expose_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        When "ENV":
            proc validate_env_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        When "WORKDIR":
            proc validate_workdir_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        When "USER":
            proc validate_user_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        When "VOLUME":
            proc validate_volume_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        When "LABEL":
            proc validate_label_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        When "ARG":
            proc validate_arg_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        When "CMD":
            proc validate_cmd_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        When "ENTRYPOINT":
            proc validate_entrypoint_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        Otherwise:
            Let warning be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Unknown instruction: ", instruction_type
            Set warning to proc string_concat from StringPrim with warning, " at line "
            Let warn_line be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line_number plus 1
            Set warning to proc string_concat from StringPrim with warning, warn_line
            proc add_dockerfile_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
    End Match
End Process

@Reasoning:
FROM accepts two argument shapes: `FROM <image>` for the simple/default-
stage case, and `FROM <image> AS <name>` for multi-stage builds where
the stage gets a referenceable name. Stage names registered here populate
analyzer.stages and are looked up by COPY --from=<name> later. The image
reference itself is delegated to validate_image_reference because the
format (registry/repo:tag@digest) is complex enough to warrant its own
parser.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads arg_count via List.list_length. If 0, builds and adds "FROM
instruction missing image name at line <n+1>" and returns. Reads
image_ref at args[0] and calls validate_image_reference. If arg_count > 2,
reads args[1] (expected "AS") and args[2] (stage name); if args[1] equals
"AS", calls register_build_stage; otherwise adds an invalid-syntax error.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Image reference originates from untrusted Dockerfile source. The image
is not pulled or inspected here - only string-validated for format -
so this proc cannot enforce supply-chain policy beyond syntactic
correctness.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "validate_from_instruction" takes analyzer as Integer, args as Integer, line_number as Integer:
    Note: Validate FROM instruction syntax and image reference

    Let arg_count be proc list_length from List with args
    If arg_count is equal to 0:
        Let error be "FROM instruction missing image name at line "
        Let line_label be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line_number plus 1
        Set error to proc string_concat from StringPrim with error, line_label
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    Let image_ref be proc list_get from List with args, 0
    proc validate_image_reference with analyzer, image_ref, line_number

    Note: Check for stage name in multi-stage builds
    If arg_count is greater than 2:
        Let as_keyword be proc list_get from List with args, 1
        Let stage_name be proc list_get from List with args, 2

        Let is_as be proc string_equals from StringCore with as_keyword, "AS"
        If is_as is equal to 1:
            proc register_build_stage with analyzer, stage_name
        Otherwise:
            Let error2 be "Invalid FROM syntax, expected AS keyword at line "
            Let line_label2 be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line_number plus 1
            Set error2 to proc string_concat from StringPrim with error2, line_label2
            proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, error2
        End If
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Validates the image reference string itself: it must be a non-empty
identifier. Docker rejects FROM lines whose image is blank or whitespace,
so an empty reference is a hard validation error keyed to the source line.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tests image_ref for non-emptiness via string_is_nonempty. On empty, builds
"FROM instruction has empty image reference at line <n+1>" and adds it to
validation_errors. A populated reference passes silently; tag/latest policy
is enforced later in check_base_image_best_practices.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_image_reference" takes analyzer as Integer, image_ref as Integer, line_number as Integer:
    Note: Validate the FROM image reference is present

    Let present be string_is_nonempty with image_ref
    If present is equal to 0:
        Let error be "FROM instruction has empty image reference at line "
        Let line_label be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line_number plus 1
        Set error to proc string_concat from StringPrim with error, line_label
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, error
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers a named build stage by appending the stage name onto the
analyzer's stages list (offset 8). This is the canonical record of stage
names that check_unused_stages and the dependency walks consult.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the stages list at offset 8 and appends stage_name when it is a
non-empty handle.
@End Implementation

Process called "register_build_stage" takes analyzer as Integer, stage_name as Integer:
    Note: Record a named multi-stage build stage

    Let present be string_is_nonempty with stage_name
    If present is equal to 1:
        Let stages be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
        proc list_append from List with stages, stage_name
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
RUN creates a new image layer by executing a shell or exec-form command
at build time, so it has three concerns: syntactic validity, security
implications (running unauthenticated `curl | sh` or installing packages
without verification are well-known attack surfaces), and layer-cost
implications. The layer_count counter is bumped here so that
analyze_layer_optimization can detect when too many RUN layers exist.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads arg_count via List.list_length. If 0, adds "RUN instruction missing
command at line <n+1>" and returns. Reads command at args[0]. Calls
check_run_security_patterns and analyze_run_layer_optimization. Reads
layer_count at offset 80, increments and writes back.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Command string is untrusted input from the Dockerfile. The security
pattern scanner here is best-effort heuristic; manual review remains
required for production images.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "validate_run_instruction" takes analyzer as Integer, args as Integer, line_number as Integer:
    Note: Validate RUN instruction and analyze for security issues

    Let arg_count be proc list_length from List with args
    If arg_count is equal to 0:
        Let error be "RUN instruction missing command at line "
        Let line_label be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line_number plus 1
        Set error to proc string_concat from StringPrim with error, line_label
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    Let command be proc list_get from List with args, 0

    Note: Check for security anti-patterns
    proc check_run_security_patterns with analyzer, command, line_number

    Note: Check for layer optimization opportunities
    proc analyze_run_layer_optimization with analyzer, command, line_number

    Note: Increment layer count
    Let current_layers be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80, current_layers plus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
The two most damaging RUN anti-patterns are piping a remote download
directly into a shell (`curl ... | sh` / `wget ... | sh`), which executes
unverified code from the network during build, and using `sudo` inside a
build where there is no interactive session. Both are surfaced as security
issues rather than warnings because they directly weaken the container's
trust boundary.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns immediately on an empty command. Scans the command for "curl" or
"wget" co-occurring with a pipe-to-shell ("| sh" / "| bash"), and for a
leading/embedded "sudo". Each match appends a line-qualified finding to
security_issues (offset 88).
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Pattern matching is substring-based and heuristic. It catches the common
spellings but cannot detect obfuscated equivalents; treat as a hint, not
a guarantee.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "check_run_security_patterns" takes analyzer as Integer, command as Integer, line_number as Integer:
    Note: Scan a RUN command string for known security anti-patterns

    Let present be string_is_nonempty with command
    If present is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let security_issues be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88
    Let line_label be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line_number plus 1

    Let has_curl be proc string_contains from StringUtils with command, "curl"
    Let has_wget be proc string_contains from StringUtils with command, "wget"
    Let pipe_sh be proc string_contains from StringUtils with command, "| sh"
    Let pipe_bash be proc string_contains from StringUtils with command, "| bash"
    Let pipes_to_shell be 0
    If pipe_sh is equal to 1:
        Set pipes_to_shell to 1
    End If
    If pipe_bash is equal to 1:
        Set pipes_to_shell to 1
    End If

    Let downloads be 0
    If has_curl is equal to 1:
        Set downloads to 1
    End If
    If has_wget is equal to 1:
        Set downloads to 1
    End If

    If downloads is equal to 1 and pipes_to_shell is equal to 1:
        Let issue be "Piping a remote download into a shell at line "
        Set issue to proc string_concat from StringPrim with issue, line_label
        proc list_append from List with security_issues, issue
    End If

    Let has_sudo be proc string_contains from StringUtils with command, "sudo"
    If has_sudo is equal to 1:
        Let issue2 be "Use of sudo in RUN command at line "
        Set issue2 to proc string_concat from StringPrim with issue2, line_label
        proc list_append from List with security_issues, issue2
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
A single RUN that chains multiple `apt-get`/package operations with `&&`
across many sub-commands is already optimal; but a RUN that runs a package
install without a matching cache-clean leaves the package index baked into
the layer. We flag `apt-get install` that lacks a `rm -rf /var/lib/apt`
cleanup as a size-optimization opportunity.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns on empty command. If the command contains "apt-get install" but
not "rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists", appends a line-qualified hint to
optimization_warnings (offset 96).
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_run_layer_optimization" takes analyzer as Integer, command as Integer, line_number as Integer:
    Note: Detect package-install RUNs that omit cache cleanup

    Let present be string_is_nonempty with command
    If present is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let installs be proc string_contains from StringUtils with command, "apt-get install"
    If installs is equal to 1:
        Let cleans be proc string_contains from StringUtils with command, "rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists"
        If cleans is equal to 0:
            Let optimization_warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
            Let line_label be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line_number plus 1
            Let warning be "apt-get install without apt-list cleanup bloats the layer at line "
            Set warning to proc string_concat from StringPrim with warning, line_label
            proc list_append from List with optimization_warnings, warning
        End If
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
COPY requires at least one source and exactly one destination - the LAST
arg is always the destination. This shape (`COPY src1 src2 ... dest`) lets
a single COPY layer bring in multiple files. We validate each source
against credential-leak patterns and bump the layer count.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads arg_count. If < 2, adds "COPY instruction requires source and
destination at line <n+1>" and returns. Reads destination at
args[arg_count-1]. Loops i in 0..arg_count-2: reads source at args[i],
calls check_copy_security_patterns. Reads layer_count at offset 80,
increments and persists.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Source paths originate from untrusted Dockerfile source. Pattern matching
catches common credential-leak antipatterns but is not exhaustive;
explicit `.dockerignore` remains the authoritative defense.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "validate_copy_instruction" takes analyzer as Integer, args as Integer, line_number as Integer:
    Note: Validate COPY instruction syntax and paths

    Let arg_count be proc list_length from List with args
    If arg_count is less than 2:
        Let error be "COPY instruction requires source and destination at line "
        Let line_label be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line_number plus 1
        Set error to proc string_concat from StringPrim with error, line_label
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    Let destination be proc list_get from List with args, arg_count minus 1

    Note: Check for security issues in paths
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than arg_count minus 1:
        Let source be proc list_get from List with args, i
        proc check_copy_security_patterns with analyzer, source, destination, line_number
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Increment layer count
    Let current_layers be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80, current_layers plus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Copying host credential material into an image layer permanently embeds the
secret in the image's history even if a later layer deletes it. The well-
known offenders are SSH keys (`.ssh`, `id_rsa`), cloud credentials
(`.aws`), and dotenv files (`.env`). Catching these at the source path is
the syntactic-side defense complementing `.dockerignore`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns on an empty source. Scans the source path for ".ssh", "id_rsa",
".aws", and ".env"; any match appends a line-qualified credential-leak
finding to security_issues (offset 88).
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Substring matching only - a path that references a secret by an unusual
name will not be caught. Defense in depth with `.dockerignore` is required.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "check_copy_security_patterns" takes analyzer as Integer, source as Integer, destination as Integer, line_number as Integer:
    Note: Scan a COPY source path for credential-leak antipatterns

    Let present be string_is_nonempty with source
    If present is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let ssh_dir be proc string_contains from StringUtils with source, ".ssh"
    Let id_rsa be proc string_contains from StringUtils with source, "id_rsa"
    Let aws_dir be proc string_contains from StringUtils with source, ".aws"
    Let dotenv be proc string_contains from StringUtils with source, ".env"

    Let leaks be 0
    If ssh_dir is equal to 1:
        Set leaks to 1
    End If
    If id_rsa is equal to 1:
        Set leaks to 1
    End If
    If aws_dir is equal to 1:
        Set leaks to 1
    End If
    If dotenv is equal to 1:
        Set leaks to 1
    End If

    If leaks is equal to 1:
        Let security_issues be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88
        Let line_label be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line_number plus 1
        Let issue be "COPY of credential-shaped path '"
        Set issue to proc string_concat from StringPrim with issue, source
        Set issue to proc string_concat from StringPrim with issue, "' at line "
        Set issue to proc string_concat from StringPrim with issue, line_label
        proc list_append from List with security_issues, issue
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
ADD is COPY with extra (URL fetch, auto-extract) powers, and Docker best
practice recommends COPY unless those powers are needed. We validate the
same source/dest arity, run the same credential-leak scan on sources, bump
the layer count, and additionally emit a best-practice warning recommending
COPY where ADD's special behaviour is not required.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads arg_count. If < 2, adds the source-and-destination error and returns.
Reads destination at args[arg_count-1]. Loops sources 0..arg_count-2 running
check_copy_security_patterns. Appends an "ADD instead of COPY" advisory to
optimization_warnings, then increments layer_count.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_add_instruction" takes analyzer as Integer, args as Integer, line_number as Integer:
    Note: Validate ADD instruction syntax and recommend COPY where possible

    Let arg_count be proc list_length from List with args
    If arg_count is less than 2:
        Let error be "ADD instruction requires source and destination at line "
        Let line_label be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line_number plus 1
        Set error to proc string_concat from StringPrim with error, line_label
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    Let destination be proc list_get from List with args, arg_count minus 1
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than arg_count minus 1:
        Let source be proc list_get from List with args, i
        proc check_copy_security_patterns with analyzer, source, destination, line_number
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let optimization_warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
    Let line_label2 be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line_number plus 1
    Let warning be "Prefer COPY over ADD unless URL fetch or auto-extract is required at line "
    Set warning to proc string_concat from StringPrim with warning, line_label2
    proc list_append from List with optimization_warnings, warning

    Let current_layers be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80, current_layers plus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
EXPOSE declares container-facing ports; we must reject empty arg lists and
non-numeric/out-of-range port specs so downstream tooling never receives a
malformed declaration. Valid specs are appended to the analyzer's
exposed_ports list at offset 16 for later aggregation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
After confirming at least one arg, walks args via List.list_length/list_get,
delegating each entry to validate_port_specification. Valid entries are
added to the analyzer's exposed_ports list (offset 16); invalid ones
generate a validation error pointing to the 1-based line number.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Args originate from untrusted Dockerfile text. Validation rejects anything
outside 1..65535 to prevent passing bogus port specs to runtime tooling.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "validate_expose_instruction" takes analyzer as Integer, args as Integer, line_number as Integer:
    Note: Validate EXPOSE instruction and track exposed ports

    Let arg_count be proc list_length from List with args
    If arg_count is equal to 0:
        Let error be "EXPOSE instruction missing port number at line "
        Let line_label be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line_number plus 1
        Set error to proc string_concat from StringPrim with error, line_label
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    Let exposed_ports be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than arg_count:
        Let port_spec be proc list_get from List with args, i
        Let is_valid_port be proc validate_port_specification with port_spec

        If is_valid_port is equal to 1:
            proc list_append from List with exposed_ports, port_spec
        Otherwise:
            Let error2 be "Invalid port specification '"
            Set error2 to proc string_concat from StringPrim with error2, port_spec
            Set error2 to proc string_concat from StringPrim with error2, "' at line "
            Let line_label2 be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line_number plus 1
            Set error2 to proc string_concat from StringPrim with error2, line_label2
            proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, error2
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
ENV declares runtime environment variables. The most important syntactic
check is that the instruction declares at least one variable; beyond that,
ENV values that look like secrets (containing PASSWORD/SECRET/TOKEN/KEY in
the key) are surfaced as security issues because they bake credentials into
the image environment.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If arg_count is 0, adds "ENV instruction missing variable at line <n+1>".
The argument list carries the variable key(s)/value(s); each entry is
scanned for credential-shaped key names and surfaced to security_issues
(offset 88) when matched.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_env_instruction" takes analyzer as Integer, args as Integer, line_number as Integer:
    Note: Validate ENV instruction and flag secret-shaped variables

    Let arg_count be proc list_length from List with args
    If arg_count is equal to 0:
        Let error be "ENV instruction missing variable at line "
        Let line_label be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line_number plus 1
        Set error to proc string_concat from StringPrim with error, line_label
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    Let security_issues be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than arg_count:
        Let entry be proc list_get from List with args, i
        Let has_pw be proc string_contains from StringUtils with entry, "PASSWORD"
        Let has_secret be proc string_contains from StringUtils with entry, "SECRET"
        Let has_token be proc string_contains from StringUtils with entry, "TOKEN"
        Let secretish be 0
        If has_pw is equal to 1:
            Set secretish to 1
        End If
        If has_secret is equal to 1:
            Set secretish to 1
        End If
        If has_token is equal to 1:
            Set secretish to 1
        End If
        If secretish is equal to 1:
            Let line_label2 be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line_number plus 1
            Let issue be "ENV defines a credential-shaped variable at line "
            Set issue to proc string_concat from StringPrim with issue, line_label2
            proc list_append from List with security_issues, issue
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
WORKDIR sets the working directory for subsequent instructions. Docker best
practice requires an absolute path; a relative WORKDIR resolves against the
previous WORKDIR and is a frequent source of surprise. We require a present
path and warn when it is not absolute.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If arg_count is 0, adds "WORKDIR instruction missing path at line <n+1>".
Otherwise reads args[0]; if its first byte is not '/' (ASCII 47), appends a
relative-path advisory to optimization_warnings (offset 96).
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_workdir_instruction" takes analyzer as Integer, args as Integer, line_number as Integer:
    Note: Validate WORKDIR instruction and require absolute paths

    Let arg_count be proc list_length from List with args
    If arg_count is equal to 0:
        Let error be "WORKDIR instruction missing path at line "
        Let line_label be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line_number plus 1
        Set error to proc string_concat from StringPrim with error, line_label
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    Let path be proc list_get from List with args, 0
    Let path_len be proc string_length from StringCore with path
    If path_len is greater than 0:
        Let first_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with path, 0
        If first_char is not equal to 47:  Note: '/'
            Let optimization_warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
            Let line_label2 be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line_number plus 1
            Let warning be "WORKDIR should use an absolute path at line "
            Set warning to proc string_concat from StringPrim with warning, line_label2
            proc list_append from List with optimization_warnings, warning
        End If
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
USER selects the runtime user. Beyond syntactic presence, declaring root
explicitly (`USER root` / `USER 0`) is the canonical privilege-escalation
risk; we flag it here so the finding is line-qualified, complementing the
whole-file final-user analysis in check_user_privileges.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If arg_count is 0, adds "USER instruction missing user at line <n+1>".
Otherwise reads args[0]; if it equals "root" or "0", appends a line-
qualified root-user finding to security_issues (offset 88).
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_user_instruction" takes analyzer as Integer, args as Integer, line_number as Integer:
    Note: Validate USER instruction and flag explicit root

    Let arg_count be proc list_length from List with args
    If arg_count is equal to 0:
        Let error be "USER instruction missing user at line "
        Let line_label be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line_number plus 1
        Set error to proc string_concat from StringPrim with error, line_label
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    Let user be proc list_get from List with args, 0
    Let is_root be proc string_equals from StringCore with user, "root"
    Let is_zero be proc string_equals from StringCore with user, "0"
    If is_root is equal to 1 or is_zero is equal to 1:
        Let security_issues be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88
        Let line_label2 be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line_number plus 1
        Let issue be "USER explicitly set to root at line "
        Set issue to proc string_concat from StringPrim with issue, line_label2
        proc list_append from List with security_issues, issue
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
VOLUME declares one or more mount points. The only structural requirement is
that at least one path is present; an empty VOLUME is a syntax error. Valid
paths are recorded into the analyzer's volumes registry for downstream
reporting.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If arg_count is 0, adds "VOLUME instruction missing path at line <n+1>".
Otherwise walks every path and appends it to the volumes list (offset 32).
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_volume_instruction" takes analyzer as Integer, args as Integer, line_number as Integer:
    Note: Validate VOLUME instruction and record mount points

    Let arg_count be proc list_length from List with args
    If arg_count is equal to 0:
        Let error be "VOLUME instruction missing path at line "
        Let line_label be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line_number plus 1
        Set error to proc string_concat from StringPrim with error, line_label
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    Let volumes be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than arg_count:
        Let path be proc list_get from List with args, i
        proc list_append from List with volumes, path
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
LABEL attaches metadata key/value pairs. A LABEL with no pairs is a syntax
error. Each declared key is recorded into the analyzer's labels registry so
check_metadata_completeness can later confirm that provenance metadata is
present.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If arg_count is 0, adds "LABEL instruction missing key-value pair at line
<n+1>". Otherwise appends every label entry to the labels list (offset 56).
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_label_instruction" takes analyzer as Integer, args as Integer, line_number as Integer:
    Note: Validate LABEL instruction and record metadata keys

    Let arg_count be proc list_length from List with args
    If arg_count is equal to 0:
        Let error be "LABEL instruction missing key-value pair at line "
        Let line_label be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line_number plus 1
        Set error to proc string_concat from StringPrim with error, line_label
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    Let labels be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than arg_count:
        Let entry be proc list_get from List with args, i
        proc list_append from List with labels, entry
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
ARG declares a build-time variable. It must name a variable; a nameless ARG
is a syntax error. Each declared name is recorded into the args registry so
the metadata audit can recognise build-arg usage.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If arg_count is 0, adds "ARG instruction missing name at line <n+1>".
Otherwise appends every argument entry to the args list (offset 64).
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_arg_instruction" takes analyzer as Integer, args as Integer, line_number as Integer:
    Note: Validate ARG instruction and record build-arg names

    Let arg_count be proc list_length from List with args
    If arg_count is equal to 0:
        Let error be "ARG instruction missing name at line "
        Let line_label be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line_number plus 1
        Set error to proc string_concat from StringPrim with error, line_label
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    Let args_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 64
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than arg_count:
        Let entry be proc list_get from List with args, i
        proc list_append from List with args_registry, entry
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
CMD supplies the default container command. An empty CMD is unusual but not
strictly illegal (an image may rely on ENTRYPOINT); however a missing
command makes the instruction meaningless, so we warn rather than error.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If arg_count is 0, appends "CMD instruction has no command at line <n+1>"
to validation_warnings. Otherwise the instruction is well-formed and no
diagnostic is emitted.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_cmd_instruction" takes analyzer as Integer, args as Integer, line_number as Integer:
    Note: Validate CMD instruction presence

    Let arg_count be proc list_length from List with args
    If arg_count is equal to 0:
        Let warning be "CMD instruction has no command at line "
        Let line_label be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line_number plus 1
        Set warning to proc string_concat from StringPrim with warning, line_label
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
ENTRYPOINT defines the fixed executable for the container. A missing
command is a hard error because, unlike CMD, an ENTRYPOINT with no
executable cannot launch anything.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If arg_count is 0, adds "ENTRYPOINT instruction missing command at line
<n+1>" to validation_errors. Otherwise it is well-formed.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_entrypoint_instruction" takes analyzer as Integer, args as Integer, line_number as Integer:
    Note: Validate ENTRYPOINT instruction presence

    Let arg_count be proc list_length from List with args
    If arg_count is equal to 0:
        Let error be "ENTRYPOINT instruction missing command at line "
        Let line_label be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with line_number plus 1
        Set error to proc string_concat from StringPrim with error, line_label
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, error
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
After per-instruction validation, the structure pass collects each
instruction's salient value into the analyzer's registries so that whole-
file phases (base-image policy, metadata audit) can operate on aggregated
data without re-walking the AST. FROM image references land in base_images;
that is the registry check_base_image_best_practices and validate_base_images
consume.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads instruction_type. For FROM, reads the image reference at node offset 8
and appends it to base_images (offset 0) when present. Other instruction
kinds have already routed their data through their validators
(ENV/LABEL/ARG/VOLUME registries), so they need no additional collection
here.
@End Implementation

Process called "collect_instruction_info" takes analyzer as Integer, instruction as Integer:
    Note: Aggregate per-instruction data into the analyzer registries

    If instruction is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 0
    If node_type is equal to NODE_FROM:
        Let image be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 8
        Let present be string_is_nonempty with image
        If present is equal to 1:
            Let base_images be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
            proc list_append from List with base_images, image
        End If
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Whole-file requirement check: every Dockerfile must contain at least one
FROM instruction, and FROM must precede any non-ARG instruction. This proc
verifies the FROM presence requirement over the full instruction list so
that even a Dockerfile whose first instruction is FROM-less is reported.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the instruction list. Walks it counting FROM occurrences. If zero
FROM instructions exist, adds "Dockerfile must contain at least one FROM
instruction" to validation_errors. (FROM-ordering is enforced separately
by validate_from_instruction_placement.)
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_required_instructions" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Ensure the Dockerfile declares the mandatory FROM instruction

    Let instructions be proc get_dockerfile_instructions with dockerfile_ast
    If instructions is equal to 0:
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, "Dockerfile must contain at least one FROM instruction"
        Return
    End If

    Let instruction_count be proc list_length from List with instructions
    Let from_count be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than instruction_count:
        Let instruction be proc list_get from List with instructions, i
        Let instruction_type be proc get_instruction_type with instruction
        Let is_from be proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction_type, "FROM"
        If is_from is equal to 1:
            Set from_count to from_count plus 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    If from_count is equal to 0:
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, "Dockerfile must contain at least one FROM instruction"
    End If
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: BUILD STAGE ANALYSIS
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Phase 2 builds the stage dependency graph by running four sub-analyses in
fixed order: identify_build_stages populates analyzer.stages (must run first),
analyze_stage_dependencies walks COPY --from references, check_unused_stages
flags stages no later COPY references, validate_stage_references catches
references to undeclared stages. The ordering is strict: references can't be
validated until the stage set is known.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls four procs in sequence: identify_build_stages, analyze_stage_dependencies,
check_unused_stages (registry + ast), validate_stage_references. No return
value - results flow into security_issues and optimization_warnings.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_build_stages" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Analyze multi-stage build structure and dependencies

    proc identify_build_stages with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
    proc analyze_stage_dependencies with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
    proc check_unused_stages with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
    proc validate_stage_references with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multi-stage builds are recognised by FROM <image> [AS <name>] occurrences;
this pass records the explicit stage names already registered by
register_build_stage and ensures the stages list reflects every named stage,
giving later passes a complete name set to validate references against.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walks the instruction list. For each FROM whose argument list yields a stage
name (arg_count > 2 with args[1] == "AS"), appends args[2] to the stages
list (offset 8) if not already present. Anonymous stages are not named here -
only referenceable named stages matter for reference validation.
@End Implementation

Process called "identify_build_stages" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Identify all named build stages in the Dockerfile

    Let instructions be proc get_dockerfile_instructions with dockerfile_ast
    If instructions is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let instruction_count be proc list_length from List with instructions
    Let stages be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than instruction_count:
        Let instruction be proc list_get from List with instructions, i
        Let instruction_type be proc get_instruction_type with instruction

        Let is_from be proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction_type, "FROM"
        If is_from is equal to 1:
            Let args be proc get_instruction_arguments with instruction
            Let arg_count be proc list_length from List with args

            If arg_count is greater than 2:
                Let stage_name be proc list_get from List with args, 2
                Let already be proc list_contains_string with stages, stage_name
                If already is equal to 0:
                    proc list_append from List with stages, stage_name
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
A reusable membership test over a list of string handles. Several stage
passes need "does this list already contain this name" semantics; centralising
it avoids duplicate inline loops and keeps the comparison (string_equals)
consistent.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walks the list comparing each element to needle via string_equals; returns 1
on the first match, 0 if the walk completes without a hit. Null list returns 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "list_contains_string" takes lst as Integer, needle as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Return 1 if lst contains a string equal to needle

    If lst is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let count be proc list_length from List with lst
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let element be proc list_get from List with lst, i
        Let same be proc string_equals from StringCore with element, needle
        If same is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Cross-stage COPY references (`COPY --from=stage src dest`) are the only way
one Docker stage references another. This walk records which named stages
are actually referenced by collecting the --from values into a per-call
referenced set, then is consumed by check_unused_stages. Here we simply
validate that any referenced stage name exists in the stage set; a reference
to an undeclared stage is recorded as a security/integrity issue.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walks instructions. For each COPY node, reads the from_stage field at COPY
offset 24; if non-empty and not a numeric external-image index, checks it
against the stages list. A reference to an unknown stage name appends a
finding to security_issues (offset 88).
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_stage_dependencies" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Validate COPY --from stage references resolve to declared stages

    Let instructions be proc get_dockerfile_instructions with dockerfile_ast
    If instructions is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let instruction_count be proc list_length from List with instructions
    Let stages be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than instruction_count:
        Let instruction be proc list_get from List with instructions, i
        Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 0

        If node_type is equal to NODE_COPY:
            Let from_stage be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 24
            Let present be string_is_nonempty with from_stage
            If present is equal to 1:
                Let is_numeric be all_digits with from_stage
                If is_numeric is equal to 0:
                    Let known be proc list_contains_string with stages, from_stage
                    If known is equal to 0:
                        Let security_issues be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88
                        Let issue be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "COPY --from references unknown stage: ", from_stage
                        proc list_append from List with security_issues, issue
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
A predicate distinguishing a numeric COPY --from index (e.g. `--from=0`,
a valid reference to the Nth prior stage or an external image) from a named
stage reference. Numeric forms are always legal and must not trip the
unknown-stage check.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for a null/empty handle. Otherwise scans every byte; returns 0 on
the first non-digit (ASCII 48..57), else 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "all_digits" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: True when value is a non-empty all-digit string

    Let present be string_is_nonempty with value
    If present is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with value
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than length:
        Let char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with value, i
        If char is less than 48 or char is greater than 57:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
A multi-stage build that declares a named stage which no later instruction
ever references (via `COPY --from=<name>` or `FROM <name>`) is wasted build
time and image-graph bloat. This pass cross-references the declared stage set
against the set of stages actually referenced; any declared-but-unreferenced
stage produces an optimization warning.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds the referenced-name set by walking instructions: every COPY's
from_stage (offset 24) and every FROM whose image equals a declared stage
name (stage-as-base reuse) contributes a reference. Then walks the declared
stages list (offset 8); each stage name absent from the referenced set
appends an "unused stage" advisory to optimization_warnings (offset 96).
@End Implementation

Process called "check_unused_stages" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Warn on declared multi-stage build stages that are never referenced

    Let stages be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    If stages is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let stage_count be proc list_length from List with stages
    If stage_count is less than 2:
        Note: Single-stage (or no named stages) builds cannot have unused stages
        Return
    End If

    Let instructions be proc get_dockerfile_instructions with dockerfile_ast
    If instructions is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let instruction_count be proc list_length from List with instructions

    Note: Collect the set of referenced stage names
    Let referenced be proc list_create from List
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than instruction_count:
        Let instruction be proc list_get from List with instructions, i
        Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 0

        If node_type is equal to NODE_COPY:
            Let from_stage be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 24
            Let copy_present be string_is_nonempty with from_stage
            If copy_present is equal to 1:
                proc list_append from List with referenced, from_stage
            End If
        End If

        If node_type is equal to NODE_FROM:
            Let from_image be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 8
            Let image_is_stage be proc list_contains_string with stages, from_image
            If image_is_stage is equal to 1:
                proc list_append from List with referenced, from_image
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: The last declared stage is the build target and is implicitly used
    Let last_index be stage_count minus 1
    Let target_stage be proc list_get from List with stages, last_index
    proc list_append from List with referenced, target_stage

    Note: Report each declared stage absent from the referenced set
    Let optimization_warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
    Let s be 0
    While s is less than stage_count:
        Let stage_name be proc list_get from List with stages, s
        Let used be proc list_contains_string with referenced, stage_name
        If used is equal to 0:
            Let warning be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Unused build stage: ", stage_name
            proc list_append from List with optimization_warnings, warning
        End If
        Set s to s plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Final stage-graph integrity check: a COPY --from that names a stage which is
declared LATER in the file (a forward reference) is illegal in Docker because
a stage can only copy from stages already built. This pass tracks the set of
stages declared so far and flags any COPY --from to a name not yet declared
as a hard validation error.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Maintains a declared-so-far set. Walks instructions in order: a FROM with a
stage name adds that name to the set; a COPY whose from_stage is a non-
numeric name not in the declared-so-far set produces a forward-reference
validation error.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_stage_references" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Reject forward references in COPY --from across build stages

    Let instructions be proc get_dockerfile_instructions with dockerfile_ast
    If instructions is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let instruction_count be proc list_length from List with instructions
    Let declared_so_far be proc list_create from List
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than instruction_count:
        Let instruction be proc list_get from List with instructions, i
        Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 0

        If node_type is equal to NODE_FROM:
            Let stage_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 32
            Let name_present be string_is_nonempty with stage_name
            If name_present is equal to 1:
                proc list_append from List with declared_so_far, stage_name
            End If
        End If

        If node_type is equal to NODE_COPY:
            Let from_stage be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 24
            Let from_present be string_is_nonempty with from_stage
            If from_present is equal to 1:
                Let is_numeric be all_digits with from_stage
                If is_numeric is equal to 0:
                    Let declared be proc list_contains_string with declared_so_far, from_stage
                    If declared is equal to 0:
                        Let error be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "COPY --from references a stage not yet declared: ", from_stage
                        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, error
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: SECURITY ANALYSIS
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Phase 4 runs four orthogonal security sub-checks: user privileges (detecting
root-running containers), sensitive data exposure (catching secrets baked
into image layers via ENV or COPY), package security (insecure download/
install patterns), and general best-practice security policy. Each is
independent so they can run in any order.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls four sub-checks sequentially: check_user_privileges,
check_sensitive_data_exposure, check_package_security,
validate_security_best_practices. All findings flow into
analyzer.security_issues (offset 88).
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
This phase is the primary defense against image security issues found
post-build. The checks here are pattern-based and best-effort; production
deployments must additionally run dedicated scanners against the built image.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "analyze_dockerfile_security" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Perform comprehensive security analysis

    proc check_user_privileges with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
    proc check_sensitive_data_exposure with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
    proc check_package_security with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
    proc validate_security_best_practices with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
End Process

@Reasoning:
Docker containers default to running as root (UID 0) if no USER instruction
overrides it. This check walks the instruction list noting the most recent
USER, and at the end determines whether the FINAL effective user is root
(either "root"/"0" string match or no USER instruction at all). Only the
LAST USER matters for the running container.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Initialises has_user_instruction=0, current_user="root", i=0. Loops
instructions: on USER, sets has_user_instruction=1 and updates current_user
from args[0] when present. After the loop, if current_user equals "root"/"0"
OR has_user_instruction is 0, appends a root-user finding to security_issues
(offset 88).
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Detection is string-comparison only; numeric forms like `0:0` are not
caught. Defense-in-depth hint, not a complete privilege analysis.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "check_user_privileges" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Check for privilege escalation and root usage

    Let instructions be proc get_dockerfile_instructions with dockerfile_ast
    If instructions is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let instruction_count be proc list_length from List with instructions
    Let has_user_instruction be 0
    Let current_user be "root"
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than instruction_count:
        Let instruction be proc list_get from List with instructions, i
        Let instruction_type be proc get_instruction_type with instruction

        Let is_user be proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction_type, "USER"
        If is_user is equal to 1:
            Set has_user_instruction to 1
            Let args be proc get_instruction_arguments with instruction
            Let arg_count be proc list_length from List with args

            If arg_count is greater than 0:
                Set current_user to proc list_get from List with args, 0
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Check if running as root in final stage
    Let is_root be proc string_equals from StringCore with current_user, "root"
    Let is_zero be proc string_equals from StringCore with current_user, "0"
    Let runs_as_root be 0
    If is_root is equal to 1:
        Set runs_as_root to 1
    End If
    If is_zero is equal to 1:
        Set runs_as_root to 1
    End If
    If has_user_instruction is equal to 0:
        Set runs_as_root to 1
    End If

    If runs_as_root is equal to 1:
        Let security_issues be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88
        proc list_append from List with security_issues, "Container running as root user - security risk"
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Secrets baked into image layers via ENV variable values or LABEL metadata
are recoverable from the image even after deletion. This pass scans ENV and
LABEL instruction arguments for credential-shaped key names (PASSWORD,
SECRET, TOKEN, API_KEY) so the user is warned before publishing the image.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walks instructions. For each ENV/LABEL node, retrieves the argument list and
scans each entry for the credential-shaped substrings; any match appends a
sensitive-data finding to security_issues (offset 88).
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Substring detection over key/value text; obfuscated secret names are not
caught. Build-time secret mounts remain the recommended mitigation.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "check_sensitive_data_exposure" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Scan ENV/LABEL values for credential-shaped data

    Let instructions be proc get_dockerfile_instructions with dockerfile_ast
    If instructions is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let instruction_count be proc list_length from List with instructions
    Let security_issues be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than instruction_count:
        Let instruction be proc list_get from List with instructions, i
        Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 0

        Let scan be 0
        If node_type is equal to NODE_ENV:
            Set scan to 1
        End If
        If node_type is equal to NODE_LABEL:
            Set scan to 1
        End If

        If scan is equal to 1:
            Let args be proc get_instruction_arguments with instruction
            Let arg_count be proc list_length from List with args
            Let j be 0
            While j is less than arg_count:
                Let entry be proc list_get from List with args, j
                Let has_pw be proc string_contains from StringUtils with entry, "PASSWORD"
                Let has_secret be proc string_contains from StringUtils with entry, "SECRET"
                Let has_token be proc string_contains from StringUtils with entry, "TOKEN"
                Let has_apikey be proc string_contains from StringUtils with entry, "API_KEY"
                Let found be 0
                If has_pw is equal to 1:
                    Set found to 1
                End If
                If has_secret is equal to 1:
                    Set found to 1
                End If
                If has_token is equal to 1:
                    Set found to 1
                End If
                If has_apikey is equal to 1:
                    Set found to 1
                End If
                If found is equal to 1:
                    proc list_append from List with security_issues, "Possible secret baked into image metadata"
                End If
                Set j to j plus 1
            End While
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Package-manager invocations in RUN commands carry security weight: installing
without verifying signatures, or disabling certificate checks
(`--allow-unauthenticated`, `--no-check-certificate`), opens the build to
supply-chain tampering. This pass scans RUN commands for those flags.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walks instructions. For each RUN node, reads the command at offset 16 and
scans for "--allow-unauthenticated" and "--no-check-certificate"; either
appends an insecure-package finding to security_issues (offset 88).
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Heuristic substring scan; covers the common spellings of certificate/sig
bypass flags but not every package manager's equivalent.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "check_package_security" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Scan RUN commands for insecure package-manager flags

    Let instructions be proc get_dockerfile_instructions with dockerfile_ast
    If instructions is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let instruction_count be proc list_length from List with instructions
    Let security_issues be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than instruction_count:
        Let instruction be proc list_get from List with instructions, i
        Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 0

        If node_type is equal to NODE_RUN:
            Let command be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 16
            Let present be string_is_nonempty with command
            If present is equal to 1:
                Let allow_unauth be proc string_contains from StringUtils with command, "--allow-unauthenticated"
                Let no_cert be proc string_contains from StringUtils with command, "--no-check-certificate"
                Let insecure be 0
                If allow_unauth is equal to 1:
                    Set insecure to 1
                End If
                If no_cert is equal to 1:
                    Set insecure to 1
                End If
                If insecure is equal to 1:
                    proc list_append from List with security_issues, "Insecure package install disables verification"
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Security best-practice aggregator: an image that performs no privilege
de-escalation AND exposes a privileged port (< 1024) is at elevated risk
because the process must run as root to bind it. This proc consults the
already-populated exposed_ports and users registries to surface that
combination as a policy advisory.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the users registry (offset 48) and exposed_ports (offset 16). If no
non-root USER was recorded AND any exposed port parses to < 1024, appends a
privileged-port-as-root advisory to security_issues (offset 88).
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_security_best_practices" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Flag privileged-port exposure without privilege de-escalation

    Let exposed_ports be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16
    If exposed_ports is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let port_count be proc list_length from List with exposed_ports
    Let has_privileged be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than port_count:
        Let port_spec be proc list_get from List with exposed_ports, i
        Let port_num be port_number_of with port_spec
        If port_num is greater than 0 and port_num is less than 1024:
            Set has_privileged to 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    If has_privileged is equal to 1:
        Note: Determine whether a non-root USER was declared
        Let instructions be proc get_dockerfile_instructions with dockerfile_ast
        Let non_root_user be 0
        If instructions is not equal to 0:
            Let instruction_count be proc list_length from List with instructions
            Let j be 0
            While j is less than instruction_count:
                Let instruction be proc list_get from List with instructions, j
                Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 0
                If node_type is equal to NODE_USER:
                    Let user be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 8
                    Let is_root be proc string_equals from StringCore with user, "root"
                    Let is_zero be proc string_equals from StringCore with user, "0"
                    Let present be string_is_nonempty with user
                    If present is equal to 1 and is_root is equal to 0 and is_zero is equal to 0:
                        Set non_root_user to 1
                    End If
                End If
                Set j to j plus 1
            End While
        End If

        If non_root_user is equal to 0:
            Let security_issues be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88
            proc list_append from List with security_issues, "Privileged port (<1024) exposed without dropping root - security risk"
        End If
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Extracts the leading numeric port from a port specification string
("80", "80/tcp", "8080-8090"). The privileged-port check only needs the
first port number, so parsing stops at the first '/' or '-' delimiter.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null/empty. Finds the first '/' or '-' (whichever comes first)
and takes the substring before it as the port digits; if neither delimiter
exists, uses the whole string. Converts via string_to_integer; returns 0 if
the digit portion is empty.
@End Implementation

Process called "port_number_of" takes port_spec as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse the leading port number from a port specification

    Let present be string_is_nonempty with port_spec
    If present is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let slash_pos be proc string_find from StringUtils with port_spec, "/", 0
    Let dash_pos be proc string_find from StringUtils with port_spec, "-", 0

    Let cut be proc string_length from StringCore with port_spec
    If slash_pos is not equal to -1 and slash_pos is less than cut:
        Set cut to slash_pos
    End If
    If dash_pos is not equal to -1 and dash_pos is less than cut:
        Set cut to dash_pos
    End If

    If cut is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let port_digits be proc string_substring from StringPrim with port_spec, 0, cut
    Return proc string_to_integer from StringPrim with port_digits
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: BASE IMAGE VALIDATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Phase 3 validates each collected base image: a FROM whose recorded image
reference is empty is a hard error, and any base image that is a bare stage
alias (matching a declared stage name) is legitimate and skipped. Real image
references are also checked for the `:latest`/missing-tag policy in
check_base_image_best_practices; here we focus on presence/integrity.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads base_images (offset 0) and its count. Loops each entry: an empty
reference appends "FROM base image reference is empty" to validation_errors.
Non-empty references pass; tag policy is enforced in the best-practices phase.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_base_images" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate collected base image references are well-formed

    Let base_images be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    If base_images is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let image_count be proc list_length from List with base_images
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than image_count:
        Let image_ref be proc list_get from List with base_images, i
        Let present be string_is_nonempty with image_ref
        If present is equal to 0:
            proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, "FROM base image reference is empty"
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: LAYER OPTIMIZATION ANALYSIS
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Phase 5 examines layer-economy concerns: each layer in a Docker image adds
storage overhead. The three sub-checks address: (1) RUN-combining
(consecutive RUNs should be merged), (2) cache-friendly ordering (rarely-
changing instructions before frequently-changing ones), (3) layer-ordering
policy (COPY application code after package installs).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls three sub-procedures: check_run_command_combining,
analyze_cache_efficiency, check_layer_ordering. All findings flow into
analyzer.optimization_warnings (offset 96).
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_layer_optimization" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Analyze layer optimization opportunities

    proc check_run_command_combining with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
    proc analyze_cache_efficiency with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
    proc check_layer_ordering with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
End Process

@Reasoning:
Each RUN instruction creates a distinct image layer. Consecutive RUN
instructions could be combined with `&&` into one layer, saving size and
ensuring temporary files created and deleted within one RUN actually leave
the image. We count runs of CONSECUTIVE RUN instructions; non-RUN
instructions reset the counter.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads instructions and count. Initialises consecutive_runs=0, i=0. Loops:
on "RUN" bumps consecutive_runs; otherwise if consecutive_runs > 1 appends a
combine warning to optimization_warnings (offset 96) and resets. After the
loop handles the trailing run of RUNs.
@End Implementation

Process called "check_run_command_combining" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Check for consecutive RUN commands that could be combined

    Let instructions be proc get_dockerfile_instructions with dockerfile_ast
    If instructions is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let instruction_count be proc list_length from List with instructions
    Let consecutive_runs be 0
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than instruction_count:
        Let instruction be proc list_get from List with instructions, i
        Let instruction_type be proc get_instruction_type with instruction

        Let is_run be proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction_type, "RUN"
        If is_run is equal to 1:
            Set consecutive_runs to consecutive_runs plus 1
        Otherwise:
            If consecutive_runs is greater than 1:
                Let optimization_warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
                Let warning be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with consecutive_runs
                Set warning to proc string_concat from StringPrim with warning, " consecutive RUN commands could be combined into one layer"
                proc list_append from List with optimization_warnings, warning
            End If
            Set consecutive_runs to 0
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Check final sequence
    If consecutive_runs is greater than 1:
        Let optimization_warnings2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
        Let warning2 be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with consecutive_runs
        Set warning2 to proc string_concat from StringPrim with warning2, " consecutive RUN commands at end could be combined"
        proc list_append from List with optimization_warnings2, warning2
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Docker's layer cache is invalidated from the first changed instruction
onward, so placing a broad `COPY . .` (which changes on every source edit)
before package-install RUNs forces the expensive installs to re-run on every
build. This pass flags a full-context COPY that precedes any RUN as a cache-
efficiency anti-pattern.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walks instructions tracking whether a full-context COPY (destination scanned
for "." source) has been seen. When a RUN appears after such a COPY, appends
a cache-efficiency advisory to optimization_warnings (offset 96), once.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_cache_efficiency" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Flag broad COPY placed before package-install RUN (cache busting)

    Let instructions be proc get_dockerfile_instructions with dockerfile_ast
    If instructions is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let instruction_count be proc list_length from List with instructions
    Let saw_broad_copy be 0
    Let reported be 0
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than instruction_count:
        Let instruction be proc list_get from List with instructions, i
        Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 0

        If node_type is equal to NODE_COPY:
            Let sources be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 8
            If sources is not equal to 0:
                Let src_count be proc list_length from List with sources
                Let s be 0
                While s is less than src_count:
                    Let src be proc list_get from List with sources, s
                    Let is_dot be proc string_equals from StringCore with src, "."
                    If is_dot is equal to 1:
                        Set saw_broad_copy to 1
                    End If
                    Set s to s plus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If

        If node_type is equal to NODE_RUN:
            If saw_broad_copy is equal to 1 and reported is equal to 0:
                Let optimization_warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
                proc list_append from List with optimization_warnings, "Broad 'COPY . .' before RUN busts the build cache - copy dependency manifests first"
                Set reported to 1
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
The recommended Dockerfile layer ordering places infrastructure setup
(package installs) before application code so that app-only edits reuse the
cached install layers. A Dockerfile that issues its last RUN after the final
COPY of application code inverts this and is flagged.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walks instructions recording the index of the last RUN and the last COPY.
If a RUN appears after the last COPY (last_run > last_copy and both exist),
appends a layer-ordering advisory to optimization_warnings (offset 96).
@End Implementation

Process called "check_layer_ordering" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Warn when a RUN follows the final COPY (suboptimal cache ordering)

    Let instructions be proc get_dockerfile_instructions with dockerfile_ast
    If instructions is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let instruction_count be proc list_length from List with instructions
    Let last_run be -1
    Let last_copy be -1
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than instruction_count:
        Let instruction be proc list_get from List with instructions, i
        Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 0

        If node_type is equal to NODE_RUN:
            Set last_run to i
        End If
        If node_type is equal to NODE_COPY:
            Set last_copy to i
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    If last_copy is not equal to -1 and last_run is greater than last_copy:
        Let optimization_warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
        proc list_append from List with optimization_warnings, "RUN after final COPY of application code reduces cache reuse - install dependencies before copying source"
    End If
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: DOCKER BEST PRACTICES VALIDATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Phase 6 (final) is the catch-all best-practices aggregator covering base
image selection, HEALTHCHECK presence, signal handling, and metadata
completeness. Each is a soft policy concern - violations don't break builds
but flag the image as non-production-ready.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls four sub-procs: check_base_image_best_practices,
check_healthcheck_configuration, validate_signal_handling,
check_metadata_completeness. Findings go to optimization_warnings or
security_issues depending on severity.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_docker_best_practices" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Validate Docker best practices compliance

    proc check_base_image_best_practices with analyzer
    proc check_healthcheck_configuration with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
    proc validate_signal_handling with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
    proc check_metadata_completeness with analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Two image-reference anti-patterns flagged here: (1) the `:latest` tag which
is a moving target making builds non-reproducible and creating a supply-chain
vector; (2) entirely missing tag, which Docker silently resolves to
`:latest`. `:latest` is a security issue; missing tag is an optimization
warning.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads base_images list (offset 0) and its count. Loops each: string_contains
test for ":latest" appends to security_issues (offset 88). A second
string_contains for ":" that is false (no tag) appends to
optimization_warnings (offset 96).
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
The `:latest` tag check is the primary supply-chain defense in this analyzer.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "check_base_image_best_practices" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Check base image selection best practices

    Let base_images be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    If base_images is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let image_count be proc list_length from List with base_images
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than image_count:
        Let image_ref be proc list_get from List with base_images, i

        Note: Check for 'latest' tag
        Let has_latest be proc string_contains from StringUtils with image_ref, ":latest"
        If has_latest is equal to 1:
            Let security_issues be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88
            Let issue be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Base image uses 'latest' tag: ", image_ref
            proc list_append from List with security_issues, issue
        End If

        Note: Check for missing tag
        Let has_colon be proc string_contains from StringUtils with image_ref, ":"
        If has_colon is equal to 0:
            Let optimization_warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
            Let warning be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Base image missing explicit tag: ", image_ref
            proc list_append from List with optimization_warnings, warning
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Production containers should declare a HEALTHCHECK so orchestrators can
detect a hung process. The absence of any HEALTHCHECK instruction is a
best-practice gap surfaced as an optimization warning.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walks instructions counting HEALTHCHECK nodes. If none are present, appends
"No HEALTHCHECK instruction" to optimization_warnings (offset 96).
@End Implementation

Process called "check_healthcheck_configuration" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Warn when no HEALTHCHECK is declared

    Let instructions be proc get_dockerfile_instructions with dockerfile_ast
    If instructions is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let instruction_count be proc list_length from List with instructions
    Let found be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than instruction_count:
        Let instruction be proc list_get from List with instructions, i
        Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 0
        If node_type is equal to NODE_HEALTHCHECK:
            Set found to 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    If found is equal to 0:
        Let optimization_warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
        proc list_append from List with optimization_warnings, "No HEALTHCHECK instruction - orchestrators cannot detect an unhealthy container"
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
A shell-form ENTRYPOINT/CMD runs the command under `/bin/sh -c`, which
becomes PID 1 and does NOT forward SIGTERM to the child, breaking graceful
shutdown. Exec form (JSON array) makes the executable PID 1 directly. The
parser records the form at the node's form field; shell-form ENTRYPOINT is
flagged here.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walks instructions. For each ENTRYPOINT node, reads the form field (offset 8;
SHELL_FORM = 2000). If shell form, appends a signal-handling advisory to
optimization_warnings (offset 96).
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_signal_handling" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Warn when ENTRYPOINT uses shell form (breaks SIGTERM forwarding)

    Let instructions be proc get_dockerfile_instructions with dockerfile_ast
    If instructions is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let instruction_count be proc list_length from List with instructions
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than instruction_count:
        Let instruction be proc list_get from List with instructions, i
        Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 0
        If node_type is equal to NODE_ENTRYPOINT:
            Let form be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instruction, 8
            If form is equal to 2000:  Note: SHELL_FORM
                Let optimization_warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
                proc list_append from List with optimization_warnings, "Shell-form ENTRYPOINT does not forward signals - use exec form (JSON array) for correct SIGTERM handling"
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Provenance metadata (a LABEL maintainer / org.opencontainers.image.* label
or a legacy MAINTAINER instruction) lets operators trace an image to its
source. The absence of any such metadata is a best-practice gap surfaced as
an optimization warning. This pass consults the already-populated labels
registry rather than re-walking the AST.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the labels registry (offset 56) and its count. If the registry is empty
(no LABEL ever recorded), appends "No metadata labels" to
optimization_warnings (offset 96). A populated registry satisfies the check.
@End Implementation

Process called "check_metadata_completeness" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Warn when the image declares no provenance metadata

    Let labels be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56
    Let label_count be 0
    If labels is not equal to 0:
        Set label_count to proc list_length from List with labels
    End If

    If label_count is equal to 0:
        Let optimization_warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
        proc list_append from List with optimization_warnings, "No metadata labels (e.g. maintainer / org.opencontainers.image.*) - image provenance cannot be traced"
    End If
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: UTILITY FUNCTIONS
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Docker EXPOSE arguments accept three formats: a bare port (`80`), port with
protocol (`80/tcp` or `80/udp`), or port range (`8080-8090` or `8080-8090/tcp`).
Other protocols are rejected. The dash-separated range form requires BOTH
endpoints to parse as integers in 1..65535. Returning Integer 0/1 lets the
caller branch cleanly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Locates `/` via string_find. If found, splits into port_part (before) and
protocol_part (after); checks protocol_part equals "tcp" or "udp". Then
operates on port_part. Locates `-`; if found, splits into start_port and
end_port and validates each via is_valid_port_number. If no dash, validates
port_part directly. Returns 1 only when every component passes.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Port spec originates from untrusted Dockerfile source. Strict 1..65535
validation prevents out-of-range values reaching runtime tooling.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "validate_port_specification" takes port_spec as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Validate Docker port specification format

    Let slash_pos be proc string_find from StringUtils with port_spec, "/", 0
    Let port_part be port_spec

    If slash_pos is not equal to -1:
        Set port_part to proc string_substring from StringPrim with port_spec, 0, slash_pos
        Let spec_len be proc string_length from StringCore with port_spec
        Let proto_len be spec_len minus slash_pos minus 1
        Let protocol_part be proc string_substring from StringPrim with port_spec, slash_pos plus 1, proto_len

        Note: Validate protocol
        Let is_tcp be proc string_equals from StringCore with protocol_part, "tcp"
        Let is_udp be proc string_equals from StringCore with protocol_part, "udp"
        If is_tcp is equal to 0 and is_udp is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for port range
    Let dash_pos be proc string_find from StringUtils with port_part, "-", 0
    If dash_pos is not equal to -1:
        Let start_port be proc string_substring from StringPrim with port_part, 0, dash_pos
        Let part_len be proc string_length from StringCore with port_part
        Let end_len be part_len minus dash_pos minus 1
        Let end_port be proc string_substring from StringPrim with port_part, dash_pos plus 1, end_len

        Let start_valid be proc is_valid_port_number with start_port
        Let end_valid be proc is_valid_port_number with end_port

        If start_valid is equal to 1 and end_valid is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Single port number
    Return proc is_valid_port_number with port_part
End Process

@Reasoning:
Final numeric check for an EXPOSE port: a 1..65535 decimal integer with at
most 5 characters. Pure validator returning 0/1 - does not raise diagnostics.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three gates: length in 1..5, every byte in '0'..'9' (ASCII 48..57), and the
parsed integer in 1..65535. Uses string_char_at from StringCore and
string_to_integer from StringPrim.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_valid_port_number" takes port_str as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if string is valid port number (1-65535)

    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with port_str
    If length is equal to 0 or length is greater than 5:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check all characters are digits
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than length:
        Let char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with port_str, i
        If char is less than 48 or char is greater than 57:  Note: Not a digit
            Return 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Convert to number and check range
    Let port_num be proc string_to_integer from StringPrim with port_str
    If port_num is less than 1 or port_num is greater than 65535:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: ERROR HANDLING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Records the first fatal failure that aborts further analysis (e.g. impossible
AST shape). Distinct from add_dockerfile_validation_error which collects
recoverable issues; this one trips the sticky has_error flag.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Writes the error_message string handle into offset 120 and sets has_error=1
at offset 128.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_dockerfile_semantic_error" takes analyzer as Integer, error_message as Integer:
    Note: Set semantic analysis error

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 120, error_message
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 128, 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Validation errors accumulate without aborting analysis so the user gets the
full set in one pass. Append-only ordering preserves source-document order.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads validation_errors List from offset 104 and appends the error_message
string handle.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_dockerfile_validation_error" takes analyzer as Integer, error_message as Integer:
    Note: Add validation error to error list

    Let errors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 104
    proc list_append from List with errors, error_message
End Process

@Reasoning:
Mirror of the error-add path for warning-level issues. Kept in a separate
List so warning-only builds proceed and the reporter applies distinct
formatting.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads validation_warnings List from offset 112 and appends the warning
message string.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_dockerfile_validation_warning" takes analyzer as Integer, warning_message as Integer:
    Note: Add validation warning to warning list

    Let warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 112
    proc list_append from List with warnings, warning_message
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PUBLIC API
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
One-shot facade used by the build driver: allocates analyzer + runs analysis
+ returns the populated analyzer for downstream consumption. Caller owns the
returned analyzer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls create_dockerfile_semantic_analyzer; on OOM returns 0. Otherwise runs
analyze_dockerfile which walks the AST and populates every registry/diagnostic
stream, then returns the analyzer.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
dockerfile_ast originates from user-supplied Dockerfiles. Analysis itself is
read-only over the AST; the diagnostic stream may carry attacker-controlled
strings which the reporter must escape before display.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "dockerfile_semantic_analyze" takes dockerfile_ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Perform semantic analysis on Dockerfile AST

    Let analyzer be proc create_dockerfile_semantic_analyzer
    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let result be proc analyze_dockerfile with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
    Return analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public accessor for the validation_errors stream so the diagnostic emitter
or IDE bridge can render the full error set. Null analyzer returns 0.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads offset 104 (validation_errors List). Borrowed pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "dockerfile_semantic_get_errors" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get validation errors from semantic analysis

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 104
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public accessor for warnings list. Separation from errors is preserved at the
API surface so IDEs can group/filter independently.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads offset 112 (validation_warnings List). Borrowed pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "dockerfile_semantic_get_warnings" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get validation warnings from semantic analysis

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 112
End Process

@Reasoning:
Security findings are collected on their own stream so security tooling can
subscribe to them without parsing free-form warning text.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads offset 88 (security_issues List). Borrowed pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "dockerfile_semantic_get_security_issues" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get security issues found during analysis

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88
End Process

@Reasoning:
Layer-count and instruction-ordering advice lives on a dedicated optimization
stream so users can opt into size hints without seeing them in a normal
warning report.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads offset 96 (optimization_warnings List). Borrowed pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "dockerfile_semantic_get_optimization_warnings" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get optimization warnings from analysis

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
End Process

@Reasoning:
Drivers need a single integer "did analysis pass" signal. Returns the actual
error count rather than 0/1 so reporters can pretty-print "N errors". A null
analyzer is treated as 1 error.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null analyzer returns 1. Otherwise reads validation_errors at offset 104 and
returns its list_length, which is 0 when analysis succeeded with no errors.
@End Implementation

Process called "dockerfile_semantic_has_errors" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if semantic analysis found any errors

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let errors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 104
    Let error_count be proc list_length from List with errors
    Return error_count
End Process
